¹ Virecta herbarum] S. Matth.iii. 4, where the Vulgate, following St. J erome, renders ἀκρίδες by the Latin “Locustae ;” the present translation, however, is supported by Euthymius and Theophylact. It might, perhaps, be conjectured that such a remarkable deviation as the present from the rendering of the Vul- gate had been made by Reginald upon the authority of St. Godric himself, founded upon his acquaintance with the traditions and usages of the East. In support of this conjecture the following passage from Tostatus may be quoted. Enumerating the various meanings assigned to the word ἀκρίδες, he says: “Alii dicunt quod istae locustae non sunt animalia, sed quaedam herbae quae habentur in deserto, quae Locustae vocantur in terra Chanaan; et de istis comedebat Johannes. Et tunc erat magna austeritas in cibo suo, scilieet, come- dere herbas crudas. Istud tenet frater Brocardus Teuthonicus, in libro suo de Terra Sancta3 dicens se fuisse in multis monasteriis apud Jordanem, in locis ubi Beatus Johannes conversabatur baptizans et praedicans, et ibi cum multis monachis saepe comedisse herbas quas illi Locustas vocant, et abundant in terra illa. Et dicunt quod illae erant Locustae quas comedebat Beatus Johannes. Istud tamen satis est 1·ationabile.”—Tostati Comment. in S. Matth. i. 393, edit. fol. Venet. 1615.
